Preamble

The GNU Affero General Public License is a free, copyleft license for software and other kinds of works.

The licenses for most software and other practical works are designed to take away your freedom to share and change the works. By contrast, our licenses are intended to guarantee your freedom to share and change all versions of a program--to make sure it remains free software for all its users.

When we speak of free software, we are referring to freedom, not price. Our General Public Licenses are designed to make sure that you have the freedom to distribute copies of free software (and charge for them if you wish), that you receive source code or can get it if you want it, that you can change the software or use pieces of it in new free programs, and that you know you can do these things.

Developers that use our licenses protect your rights with two steps: (1) assert copyright on the software, and (2) offer you this License giving you legal permission to copy, distribute and/or modify it.

For a developer's and publisher's protection, the AGPL is strong, ensuring that the software cannot be turned into a proprietary system. It is also designed to be effective in an environment where a program's functionality is provided to users over a computer network. The AGPL requires that any software whose functionality is provided to users over a network also makes its source code available.

This license is designed to make sure that no one is denied the opportunity to enjoy the benefits of free software, whether for their own use or for the benefit of a community. The AGPL is designed to prevent a user from being locked into a proprietary system while the developer takes the benefits of the user's creativity and effort.

The AGPL is a new license, but it is an extension of the GNU General Public License. You can find the full text of the AGPL at the GNU website.

